Add a video: Automatically Build and Publish Node and Electron Applications for Linux (#450)

I gave a talk a few weeks ago about automatically building and publishing Node.JS and Electron applications for Linux using Snapcraft. Of particular interest to Electron developers is that `electron-builder` has first class support for snaps and publishing in the snap store gives feature parity with the built-in auto-update features available in Electron for Windows and macOS. Snaps of Electron applications published in the store will be discoverable via the Software store installed by default in all major Linux distributions.

This pull request adds the video of that talk.

Add electron-is

*Added 'electron-is' library under 'Tools' section.*
_______________________________________________________________________
**Description:**
An 'is' utility for Electron.
[electron-is](https://github.com/delvedor/electron-is) provides a set of isomorphic 'is' APIs, that you can use it both in main and renderer process.

**Why it should be included:**
I think it can be a useful tool, it's pretty handy and makes the code easier to read.

*Ps: I hope you find it useful, I'm open to suggestions and improvements!*

Closes #264

Add Electron talk (#262)

This talk was given at Forward 4 Web Summit, Feb 2016 about the "Perks of
the New Desktop".

It begins with an introduction about Electron, a basic overview of how
it works, then goes on to discuss a few key benefits of this development
environment:

1. Native experiences
2. Offline & data storage
3. Modern performance tools
4. Extensibility

The talk was professionally recorded by the Forward Web Summit team and
has both slides and live demos over the course of 45 minutes.

Add babel-preset-electron

The existing babel presets are overkill for Electron. Latest Chromium and
Node support a large majority of ES6 features natively. There's no reason
to compile all `() => {}` calls to babel's bound function indirection.
There's no reason to add a bunch of boilerplate code weight that these
platforms already support.

babel-preset-electron carefully chooses the minimal set of babel plugins
necessary to support ES6 and stage-0 and up.

The version of the repo tracks the Electron version that it has been
tested on.

This has been battle-tested in [Nylas N1](https://github.com/nylas/n1) for
the latest Electron versions. As more Electron versions come out,
babel-preset-electron will continue to be tagged.
